Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Ineligible Voting Notice and Acknowledgement.
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief.

AS TO THE CHARGE AS AMENDED:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he/she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.
*
  Court found the state has satisfied victims' rights law.  Statements made as to sentencing.  Additional statements made by Dinisia S.  Court ordered defendant to serve 12 months in the House of Correction, with 3 days credit for time served.
.
COURT IMPOSED BUT STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on Probation with the State of Wisconsin, Department of Corrections for a period of 2 years with the following conditions:
-Defendant to serve 30 days straight time FORTHWITH in the House of Correction as a condition time sentence, with 0 days credit.
-Defendant to serve 60 days in the House of Correction as a condition time sentence, STAYED until next court date.
-Mental health assessment and comply with all recommended treatment.
-Successfully complete Batterer's Intervention programming.
-AODA assessment and treatment.
-Absolute sobriety-no illegal drug or alcohol.
-Random urine screens.
-No contact with the victim without approval of the Court.
-Obtain/maintain employment.
-No firearms or dangerous weapons.
-Restitution set at $1039.69; payable to the Crime Victims Compensation Fund; to be paid first and foremost.  If not paid during probation, to be docketed as a civil judgment.
-Pay all applicable court costs during period of probation.  If not paid during probation, to be docketed as a civil judgment.
.
Court ordered that the defendant cannot vote until civil rights are restored upon completion of sentence.
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.
.
Defendant to provide a DNA sample, if not already provided, and pay all appropriate costs, if not already paid, to be docketed as a civil judgment.
